Here is a possible implementation of a function that converts Markdown to HTML:
```
#include <string>
#include <stdexcept>
#include <boost/algorithm/string/replace.hpp>
#include <boost/algorithm/string/join.hpp>
#include <boost/algorithm/string/split.hpp>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    // Replace \r\n with <br />
    std::string text = markdown;
    boost::replace_all(text, "\r\n", "<br />");

    // Replace # with <h1> and <h2> etc.
    text = boost::replace_all_copy(text, "#", "<h1>");
    text = boost::replace_all_copy(text, "##", "<h2>");
    text = boost::replace_all_copy(text, "###", "<h3>");
    text = boost::replace_all_copy(text, "####", "<h4>");
    text = boost::replace_all_copy(text, "#####", "<h5>");
    text = boost::replace_all_copy(text, "######", "<h6>");

    // Replace \* with <strong>
    text = boost::replace_all_copy(text, "*", "<strong>");

    // Replace [ ]( ) with <a href=>
    boost::smatch what;
    while (boost::regex_search(text, what, boost::regex("\\[(.*?)\\]\\((.*?)\\)"))) {
        std::string link = what[1].str();
        std::string href = what[2].str();
        text = boost::replace_all_copy(text, "[" + link + "](/" + href + ")", "<a href=\"" + href + "\">" + link + "</a>");
    }

    // Replace ![ ]( ) with <img src=>
    while (boost::regex_search(text, what, boost::regex("\\!(.*?)\\]\\((.*?)\\)"))) {
        std::string img = what[1].str();
        std::string href = what[2].str();
        text = boost::replace_all_copy(text, "![" + img + "](/" + href + ")", "<img src=\"" + href + "\">");
    }

    // Replace ` ` with <code>
    text = boost::replace_all_copy(text, "`", "<code>");

    return text;
}
```
This function uses the Boost library to perform the replacements. It replaces the following Markdown syntax with HTML:

* `\r\n` with `<br />`
* `#` with `<h1>`, `<h2>`, etc.
* `*` with `<strong>`
* `[ ]( )` with `<a href=`
* `![ ]( )` with `<img src=`
* ` ` with `<code>`

Note that this is a simplified implementation and may not cover all possible Markdown syntax. You may need to add additional replacements depending on the specific requirements of your application.

Also, this implementation uses Boost's regular expressions to search for Markdown syntax, which may not be efficient for large input strings. You may want to consider using a more efficient parsing library, such as Marked or CommonMark.

